<doc id="217548" wikidata="Q2051983" url="?curid=217548" title="Conjugate transpose">
<text>In mathematics, the conjugate transpose, also known as the Hermitian transpose, of an formula_1 complex matrix formula_2 is an formula_3 matrix obtained by transposing formula_2 and applying complex conjugation to each entry (the complex conjugate of formula_5 being formula_6, for real numbers formula_7 and formula_8). There are several notations, such as formula_9 or formula_10, formula_11, or (often in physics) formula_12.

For real matrices, the conjugate transpose is just the transpose, formula_13.

==Definition==
The conjugate transpose of an formula_1 matrix formula_2 is formally defined by

|cellpadding= 6
|border
|border colour = #0073CF
|background colour=#F5FFFA}}

where the subscript formula_16 denotes the formula_17-th entry (matrix element), for formula_18 and formula_19, and the overbar denotes a scalar complex conjugate.

This definition can also be written as
:formula_20

where formula_21 denotes the transpose and formula_22 denotes the matrix with complex conjugated entries.

Other names for the conjugate transpose of a matrix are Hermitian transpose, Hermitian conjugate, adjoint matrix or transjugate. The conjugate transpose of a matrix formula_2 can be denoted by any of these symbols:
* formula_10, commonly used in linear algebra
* formula_9, commonly used in linear algebra
* formula_26 (sometimes pronounced as &quot;A dagger&quot;), commonly used in quantum mechanics
* formula_27, although this symbol is more commonly used for the Moore–Penrose pseudoinverse

In some contexts, formula_10 denotes the matrix with only complex conjugated entries and no transposition.

==Example==
Suppose we want to calculate the conjugate transpose of the following matrix formula_2.
:formula_30
We first transpose the matrix:
:formula_31
Then we conjugate every entry of the matrix:
:formula_32

==Basic remarks==
A square matrix formula_2 with entries formula_34 is called
* Hermitian or self-adjoint if formula_35; i.e., formula_36.
* Skew Hermitian or antihermitian if formula_37; i.e., formula_38.
* Normal if formula_39.
* Unitary if formula_40, equivalently formula_41, equivalently formula_42.

Even if formula_2 is not square, the two matrices formula_44 and formula_45 are both Hermitian and in fact positive semi-definite matrices.

The conjugate transpose &quot;adjoint&quot; matrix formula_9 should not be confused with the adjugate, formula_47, which is also sometimes called &quot;adjoint&quot;.

The conjugate transpose of a matrix formula_2 with real entries reduces to the transpose of formula_2, as the conjugate of a real number is the number itself.

The conjugate transpose can be motivated by noting that complex numbers can be usefully represented by formula_50 real matrices, obeying matrix addition and multiplication:
formula_51

That is, denoting each &quot;complex&quot; number formula_52 by the &quot;real&quot; formula_50 matrix of the linear transformation on the Argand diagram (viewed as the &quot;real&quot; vector space formula_54), affected by complex &quot;formula_52&quot;-multiplication on formula_56.

Thus, an formula_1 matrix of complex numbers could be well represented by a formula_58 matrix of real numbers. The conjugate transpose, therefore, arises very naturally as the result of simply transposing such a matrix—when viewed back again as an formula_3 matrix made up of complex numbers.

For an explanation of the notation used here, we begin by representing complex numbers formula_60 as the rotation matrix, that is,
formula_61
Since formula_62, we are led to the matrix representations of the unit numbers as
formula_63

A general complex number formula_64 is then represented as formula_65 The complex conjugate operation (that sends formula_66 to formula_67 for real formula_68) is encoded as the matrix transpose.

==Properties==
* formula_69 for any two matrices formula_2 and formula_71 of the same dimensions.
* formula_72 for any complex number formula_52 and any formula_1 matrix formula_2.
* formula_76 for any formula_1 matrix formula_2 and any formula_79 matrix formula_71. Note that the order of the factors is reversed.
* formula_81 for any formula_1 matrix formula_2, i.e. Hermitian transposition is an involution.
* If formula_2 is a square matrix, then formula_85 where formula_86 denotes the determinant of formula_2 .
* If formula_2 is a square matrix, then formula_89 where formula_90 denotes the trace of formula_2.
* formula_2 is invertible if and only if formula_9 is invertible, and in that case formula_94.
* The eigenvalues of formula_9 are the complex conjugates of the eigenvalues of formula_2.
* formula_97 for any formula_1 matrix formula_2, any vector in formula_100 and any vector formula_101. Here, formula_102 denotes the standard complex inner product on formula_103, and similarly for formula_104.

==Generalizations==
The last property given above shows that if one views formula_2 as a linear transformation from Hilbert space formula_106 to formula_107 then the matrix formula_9 corresponds to the adjoint operator of formula_109. The concept of adjoint operators between Hilbert spaces can thus be seen as a generalization of the conjugate transpose of matrices with respect to an orthonormal basis.

Another generalization is available: suppose formula_110 is a linear map from a complex vector space formula_111 to another, formula_112, then the complex conjugate linear map as well as the transposed linear map are defined, and we may thus take the conjugate transpose of formula_110 to be the complex conjugate of the transpose of formula_110. It maps the conjugate dual of formula_112 to the conjugate dual of formula_111.

